What is a DTO?

A DTO (Data Transfer Object) is a simple Java class used to transfer data between layers of
an application, especially between the backend and the client in REST APIs. DTOs usually
contain only fields and getters/setters, without business logic.

Why use DTOs?

(i)   To control what data is exposed to the client (e.g., hide sensitive fields).
(ii)  To shape the response format (e.g., combine fields, rename properties).
(iii) To decouple your internal entity structure from the API contract.


How Does Java Map Entities to DTOs?
Java does not automatically map entities to DTOs. You need to manually convert (map) your
entity objects to DTOs, or use libraries like MapStruct or ModelMapper to automate this
process.

Serialization
When you return a DTO from a Spring REST controller, Spring (using Jackson by default)
serializes the DTO object to JSON (or XML) for the HTTP response. Serialization means
converting the Java object into a format (like JSON) that can be sent over the network.

Example:

public class UserDTO {
    private String name;
    private String email;
    // getters and setters
}

Manual Mapping Example:

public UserDTO toDTO(User user) {
    UserDTO dto = new UserDTO();
    dto.setName(user.getName());
    dto.setEmail(user.getEmail());
    return dto;
}

Controller Example:

@GetMapping("/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<UserDTO> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    User user = userRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();
    UserDTO dto = toDTO(user);
    return ResponseEntity.ok(dto);
}

Automatic Mapping (Optional):

You can use libraries like MapStruct or ModelMapper to automate the mapping process,
reducing boilerplate code.

Summary:
A DTO is just a class for transferring data.
Java does not automatically map entities to DTOs; you must do it manually or use a mapping
library.
Spring serializes the DTO to JSON for the API response.
DTOs help control what data is exposed and keep your API contract stable.



What is JSON?

JSON stands for JavaScript Object Notation. It is a lightweight data-interchange format that
is easy for humans to read and write, and easy for machines to parse and generate